**Creating a User Cart Session in PHP**
====================================================

In this example, we will create a simple user cart system that allows users to add and remove items from their cart. We will use PHP sessions to store the cart data.

**Step 1: Create a Cart Class**
-----------------------------

Create a new file called `cart.php` with the following code:
```php
class Cart {
    private $items;

    public function __construct() {
        $this->items = array();
    }

    public function add($item, $quantity) {
        if (array_key_exists($item, $this->items)) {
            $this->items[$item] += $quantity;
        } else {
            $this->items[$item] = $quantity;
        }
    }

    public function remove($item) {
        if (array_key_exists($item, $this->items)) {
            unset($this->items[$item]);
        }
    }

    public function getItems() {
        return $this->items;
    }
}
```
This `Cart` class has methods to add and remove items from the cart, as well as retrieve the entire cart.

**Step 2: Initialize the Cart Session**
--------------------------------------

In your PHP script (e.g. `index.php`), initialize the cart session by creating a new instance of the `Cart` class:
```php
session_start();

$cart = new Cart();
```
**Step 3: Add Items to the Cart**
-------------------------------

Create an HTML form that allows users to add items to their cart:
```html
<form action="" method="post">
    <input type="text" name="item" placeholder="Item Name">
    <input type="number" name="quantity" value="1">
    <button type="submit">Add to Cart</button>
</form>
```
In your PHP script, retrieve the form data and add it to the cart:
```php
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] == 'POST') {
    $item = $_POST['item'];
    $quantity = (int) $_POST['quantity'];

    $cart->add($item, $quantity);
}
```
**Step 4: Display Cart Contents**
-------------------------------

Create an HTML list that displays the contents of the cart:
```html
<ul>
    <?php foreach ($cart->getItems() as $item => $quantity): ?>
        <li><?= $item ?> x <?= $quantity ?></li>
    <?php endforeach; ?>
</ul>
```
**Step 5: Remove Items from Cart**
-------------------------------

Create a link to remove an item from the cart:
```html
<a href="#" class="remove-item">Remove Item</a>
```
In your PHP script, retrieve the item ID and remove it from the cart:
```php
if (isset($_GET['remove'])) {
    $item = $_GET['remove'];

    $cart->remove($item);
}
```
**Full Example Code**
--------------------

Here is the full example code:
```php
<?php
session_start();

$cart = new Cart();

if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] == 'POST') {
    $item = $_POST['item'];
    $quantity = (int) $_POST['quantity'];

    $cart->add($item, $quantity);
}

if (isset($_GET['remove'])) {
    $item = $_GET['remove'];

    $cart->remove($item);
}
?>

<form action="" method="post">
    <input type="text" name="item" placeholder="Item Name">
    <input type="number" name="quantity" value="1">
    <button type="submit">Add to Cart</button>
</form>

<ul>
    <?php foreach ($cart->getItems() as $item => $quantity): ?>
        <li><?= $item ?> x <?= $quantity ?></li>
    <?php endforeach; ?>
</ul>

<?php foreach ($cart->getItems() as $item => $quantity): ?>
    <a href="?remove=<?= $item ?>" class="remove-item">Remove Item</a>
<?php endforeach; ?>
```
This is a basic example of how to create a user cart session in PHP. You can customize and expand this code to suit your specific needs.

